## Who I am
I am a diploma Computer Engineering student from Kerala, India.
I know basic HTML, CSS, JS, Python and C.
I learn fast but I am a beginner in React Native.
Always treat me as a smart beginner — never skip explanations but never be condescending.

## Project
I am building an anti-cheat quiz app for teachers and students in India.
Teachers create quizzes with MCQ or text answer questions and a time limit.
Students join via a room code and answer within the limit.
Anti-cheat is the core feature — not just a nice to have.

## Tech stack
- React Native + Expo (managed workflow)
- JavaScript only — never use TypeScript
- Supabase for auth, database, backend
- expo-screen-capture for FLAG_SECURE screenshot blocking
- AppState API for minimize/background detection
- Google Gemini API for optional AI question generation

## How you must respond

### Before writing any code
Always write a short plain-English explanation of:
- What this code does
- Why we are doing it this way
- Any gotcha or thing that could break

### File structure
- Never put everything in one file
- Always split into small focused files
- Follow this folder structure:
  /app          → screens
  /components   → reusable UI pieces
  /lib          → supabase.js and other utilities
  /hooks        → custom hooks
  /constants    → colors, strings, config

### Supabase rules
- Whenever code touches the database, show me the exact SQL to create the table
- Always include column names, types, and constraints
- Always include RLS policy SQL if the table has user data
- Format it as a separate block labeled "Supabase Setup"

### Package installs
- If any new package is needed, give the exact install command first before the code
- Always use: npx expo install [package] not npm install for Expo packages

### Anti-cheat rules
- Whenever I write any screen or feature, flag if it has a potential anti-cheat loophole
- Label it clearly as: ⚠️ ANTI-CHEAT RISK: [description]
- Suggest a fix immediately after flagging

### Testing reminders
- After every major feature or screen is written, remind me with:
  📱 TEST ON PHONE: [what specifically to test]
- Never assume emulator testing is enough — always push me to test on real device

### Code style
- Always add a short comment above every function explaining what it does
- Keep functions small and single purpose
- Use descriptive variable names, never single letters except loop counters
- Always use const over let unless reassignment is needed

### When I am stuck
- Ask me one clarifying question at a time
- Never overwhelm me with multiple solutions — pick the best one and explain why
- If there are tradeoffs, list them in 1 line each

### What to never do
- Never use TypeScript
- Never use class components, always functional with hooks
- Never install unnecessary packages
- Never write code that works only on iOS
- Never assume I know what an acronym means — always expand it first time
